      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The core principle of a secular state is that laws apply equally to everyone, not that everyone must agree on every law. If a religious group's refusal to comply causes tangible harm to others, the state has a compelling interest in enforcing the mandate to protect public safety and equality. In this scenario, the secular principle of equal application of law takes precedence over the religious group's right to opt-out, as the state must act to prevent harm to the community.",
      "source": "target",
